            <div type="a">
                <column>1</column>
                <head>Response to the Rev. Mr. Tebbs</head>
                <origin/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <commentary/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Tebbs</ln>
                        <fn>F.C.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Response to Tebbs letter in the same issue. Tebbs criticized the Spectator
                    for publishing a letter written by "Conservator" that was critical of camp
                    meetings. Spectator responds to Tebbs by invoking right of freedom of speech and
                    defends itself against charges of Anti-Methodism.</summary>
                <note>aubrowser/ssaug59.html#8.16a</note>
            </div>
            <div type="l">
                <column>4</column>
                <head>For the Spectator; A Word to the Editors of the Spectator</head>
                <origin/>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer>F. C. Tebbs; Churchville, Aug. 9th, 1859</trailer>
                <commentary/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Tebbs</ln>
                        <fn>F.C.</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf/>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Rev. Tebbs writes to the Spectator to complain about the Spectator's
                    publication on August 2nd of a letter critical of Methodist Camp Meetings. Tebbs
                    argues that the letter, written by "Conservator," was insulting and injurious to
                    the Spectator's character, and that it incorrectly associated politics and
                    religion.</summary>
                <note>aubrowser/ssaug59.html#8.16b</note>
            </div>
            <div type="a">
                <column>3</column>
                <head>Judge Douglas on the Slave Trade</head>
                <origin>Vindicator</origin>
                <excerpt/>
                <transcript/>
                <trailer/>
                <commentary/>
                <names>
                    <name>
                        <ln>Peyton</ln>
                        <fn>John</fn>
                        <sf/>
                        <pf>Col.</pf>
                    </name>
                </names>
                <summary>Letter from Stephen A. Douglas to Col. Peyton in which Douglas presents his
                    views on the African slave trade, objecting to it on constitutional grounds.
                    Spectator takes Gov. Wise's position--reopening the trade would offend the
                    morals of most Southern slaveholders.</summary>
            </div>
